that system is, I'll take you back to UFC 1 and talk about the

49
00:04:05,256 --> 00:04:09,099
grappling system there. So it's pretty straightforward kind of

50
00:04:09,119 --> 00:04:12,821
stuff. So when you take the guy to the ground, you start off in

51
00:04:12,881 --> 00:04:14,823
some kind of idle depending on what position you're in.

52
00:04:15,543 --> 00:04:17,407
The top fighter has a bunch of things he can do.

53
00:04:17,448 --> 00:04:19,111
The bottom fighter has a bunch of things he can do.

54
00:04:20,314 --> 00:04:23,220
Let's simplify it a little bit and say the top guy can go left

55
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:25,284
or right, and the bottom guy can go left or right.

56
00:04:27,577 --> 00:04:30,478
So if the top guy presses to the left,

57
00:04:31,299 --> 00:04:33,780
he'll play an animation of him doing something to the left.

58
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:36,381
That could be a submission, a transition attempt.

59
00:04:36,421 --> 00:04:38,842
In this case, he's trying to pass the bottom guy's guard

60
00:04:39,602 --> 00:04:40,642
by pressing down on the knee.

61
00:04:41,122 --> 00:04:43,983
So you've got a start animation to initiate the action.

62
00:04:44,023 --> 00:04:47,125
You've got an idle pose where the game kind of figures

63
00:04:47,165 --> 00:04:48,305
out the transition logic.

64
00:04:48,825 --> 00:04:50,966
And then you have a cancel animation

65
00:04:51,026 --> 00:04:52,927
to bring you back from where you came from,

66
00:04:53,167 --> 00:04:55,868
and a finish animation that executes the technique

67
00:04:55,908 --> 00:04:56,908
and takes you to where you're going.

68
00:04:58,879 --> 00:05:02,020
Similarly, the guy on the bottom presses to the right,

69
00:05:02,060 --> 00:05:05,482
he'll play some move in that direction.

70
00:05:05,742 --> 00:05:07,222
Similar thing, a submission, transition,

71
00:05:07,242 --> 00:05:07,742
something like that.

72
00:05:11,204 --> 00:05:14,585
So what happens if the top guy presses to the left

73
00:05:14,725 --> 00:05:16,166
and the bottom guy presses to the left

74
00:05:16,286 --> 00:05:17,186
at the exact same time?

75
00:05:18,006 --> 00:05:19,867
So in UFC 1,

76
00:05:23,988 --> 00:05:25,489
the top guy pressed to the left,

77
00:05:25,589 --> 00:05:26,970
he would play his transition animation.

78
00:05:28,539 --> 00:05:30,479
But if the bottom guy also pressed to the right

79
00:05:30,579 --> 00:05:33,920
and the game registered the input just one frame later,

80
00:05:34,260 --> 00:05:35,320
he would get absolutely nothing.

81
00:05:35,640 --> 00:05:39,281
No response from the game that he had done anything.

82
00:05:39,341 --> 00:05:40,882
He'd be locked out of any transitions.

83
00:05:40,982 --> 00:05:42,922
The only thing he could do is recognize

84
00:05:42,942 --> 00:05:44,702
that the top fighter had started a transition

85
00:05:45,123 --> 00:05:46,423
and play a denial animation,

86
00:05:46,883 --> 00:05:48,683
which just prevents him from doing his action.

87
00:05:49,244 --> 00:05:51,184
So this wasn't very good for users.

88
00:05:51,304 --> 00:05:52,225
They felt frustrated.

89
00:05:53,605 --> 00:05:55,226
Oftentimes, they'd be pressing on the stick

90
00:05:55,266 --> 00:05:56,186
and get no response.

91
00:05:56,246 --> 00:05:57,647
They thought the game was broken.

92
00:05:57,707 --> 00:05:58,467
It's unresponsive.

93
00:05:58,507 --> 00:05:59,527
I don't understand how to play.

94
00:06:00,668 --> 00:06:02,788
Just generally a bad, bad experience for people.

95
00:06:07,015 --> 00:06:08,937
So in an ideal world, we want something like this,

96
00:06:09,418 --> 00:06:13,462
where top guy presses to the left, and he gets an action.

97
00:06:13,502 --> 00:06:15,565
Bottom guy presses to the right, he also gets an action.

98
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:17,927
So the two players could act independent of each other,

99
00:06:19,069 --> 00:06:21,031
playing an animation that corresponded

100
00:06:21,051 --> 00:06:22,612
to what they were trying to do, no matter

101
00:06:22,653 --> 00:06:23,754
what the other guy was trying to do.

102
00:06:23,974 --> 00:06:27,818
Increase responsiveness, increase that sense

103
00:06:27,898 --> 00:06:29,120
of engagement with the game.

104
00:06:33,563 --> 00:06:36,043
So let's get a sense of what kind of numbers

105
00:06:36,083 --> 00:06:38,904
we're looking at in order to support a feature like that.

106
00:06:39,664 --> 00:06:42,585
So just in full guard, this position here,

107
00:06:43,445 --> 00:06:45,905
let's say the top guy has eight possible transitions.

108
00:06:45,925 --> 00:06:48,766
He could do eight transition submissions, whatever.

109
00:06:48,826 --> 00:06:51,347
So left, right, up, down, and then holding a modifier,

110
00:06:51,547 --> 00:06:52,247
left, right, up, down.

111
00:06:53,127 --> 00:06:55,507
And the bottom guy also has eight transitions, say,

112
00:06:55,707 --> 00:06:56,228
for example.

113
00:06:57,068 --> 00:06:57,548
Similar deal.

114
00:06:59,497 --> 00:07:02,538
This would represent all the different idle states

115
00:07:02,718 --> 00:07:04,880
that the players could get into in full guard.

116
00:07:07,121 --> 00:07:08,842
It's not 100% accurate.

117
00:07:09,262 --> 00:07:12,044
This is kind of the back of the napkin kind of calculations

118
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:14,585
we were doing at the beginning to see what we were up against

119
00:07:14,625 --> 00:07:15,486
to try and implement this.

120
00:07:15,506 --> 00:07:19,128
So you're looking at 8 times 8, 64 different states.

121
00:07:20,489 --> 00:07:22,370
That'd be like top guy's going to the right,

122
00:07:22,410 --> 00:07:24,191
bottom guy's going to the left, top guy's going to the right,

123
00:07:24,211 --> 00:07:25,091
bottom guy's going down.

124
00:07:25,211 --> 00:07:26,792
All those permutations, right?

125
00:07:28,936 --> 00:07:32,460
So in order to figure out what kind of animations we need,

126
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:33,801
we need four different animations

127
00:07:33,841 --> 00:07:34,882
for each one of those states.

128
00:07:35,162 --> 00:07:37,385
We need something that takes you to that state,

129
00:07:37,765 --> 00:07:39,947
an idle animation once you're in that state,

130
00:07:40,408 --> 00:07:42,590
a cancel that brings you back to the state you came from,

131
00:07:43,010 --> 00:07:44,792
and then a success animation that

132
00:07:44,812 --> 00:07:46,894
takes you to wherever you're going from each of those states.

133
00:07:46,914 --> 00:07:47,815
So we multiply by four.

134
00:07:49,430 --> 00:07:52,594
And then the game has 15 different ground positions.

135
00:07:52,714 --> 00:07:54,537
So assuming every ground position

136
00:07:54,597 --> 00:07:57,501
has the same level of complexity as guard, which they don't,

137
00:07:57,601 --> 00:08:00,825
but some are close, some are bigger, some are smaller,

138
00:08:00,845 --> 00:08:02,688
we've got to multiply that number by 15.

139
00:08:02,748 --> 00:08:04,831
So we've got a really big number here.

140
00:08:05,591 --> 00:08:11,976
To put that into context, this little piece that I cut out at the bottom, that's the number

141
00:08:11,996 --> 00:08:17,439
of animations that we built for the entire ground game in UFC 1, and the big picture

142
00:08:17,479 --> 00:08:20,862
is what we would need to build in order to support this system for UFC 2.

143
00:08:21,842 --> 00:08:26,346
with the same budget, the same timeline, same number of animators, that kind of stuff.

144
00:08:26,386 --> 00:08:30,549
So on the face of it, it looks absolutely impossible unless we can come up with some

145
00:08:30,809 --> 00:08:35,112
kind of procedural system or something, just some way to optimize this so that we can get

146
00:08:35,172 --> 00:08:37,814
like a tenfold increase in content creation.

147
00:08:38,875 --> 00:08:39,635
Not trivial at all.

148
00:08:41,593 --> 00:08:45,436
So before I dive into how we did that, I want to talk about RelativeIK.

149
00:08:45,577 --> 00:08:50,440
So RelativeIK existed in EA MMA like four years ago.

150
00:08:50,460 --> 00:08:52,722
It existed in EA UFC.

151
00:08:53,863 --> 00:08:56,845
It's used by a bunch of different games in EA Sports.

152
00:08:57,566 --> 00:09:03,710
It's a system primarily designed for playing two-player animations on characters of different scales.

153
00:09:04,110 --> 00:09:07,733
That was kind of its first purpose, and it's taken on a different meaning this year for us.

154
00:09:09,815 --> 00:09:12,317
I talked about it a little bit last year, but I'm going to dive into some details.

155
00:09:12,437 --> 00:09:15,380
Same rules apply. I'm not allowed to show any of the editors in our tool,

156
00:09:15,400 --> 00:09:20,205
but I kind of mocked them up a little bit in PowerPoint to give you an idea of how it works.

157
00:09:20,305 --> 00:09:24,269
So, yeah, two-player animations. Let's take a look at a concrete example here.

158
00:09:24,670 --> 00:09:28,814
So in this one, the bottom fighter is reaching up and grabbing the top fighter's head,

159
00:09:29,435 --> 00:09:30,956
and then canceling back into the idle.

160
00:09:32,197 --> 00:09:32,398
So...

161
00:09:33,895 --> 00:09:40,137
What does that look like if we make the bottom fighter's arm comically large?

162
00:09:42,977 --> 00:09:45,818
Obviously the contact points don't line up.

163
00:09:46,898 --> 00:09:48,119
The animation completely breaks.

164
00:09:48,899 --> 00:09:53,620
So, with the relative IK system, what we do is we offer a constraint

165
00:09:54,520 --> 00:09:58,181
between the left hand of the bottom fighter and the head of the top fighter.

166
00:09:59,021 --> 00:10:01,763
And we bake out the position of the hand relative to the head

167
00:10:02,263 --> 00:10:04,805
into a new channel in the rig for every frame

168
00:10:05,065 --> 00:10:05,746
of that animation.

169
00:10:06,686 --> 00:10:08,047
This is not how it works under the hood,

170
00:10:08,087 --> 00:10:10,969
but conceptually think of it as a bone that's

171
00:10:11,009 --> 00:10:12,750
parented to the head of the top fighter

172
00:10:13,191 --> 00:10:17,974
in the top fighter's rig that's just constrained to the hand,

173
00:10:18,394 --> 00:10:20,075
say, in MotionBuilder, and then baked out

174
00:10:20,115 --> 00:10:21,036
with that global position.

175
00:10:22,277 --> 00:10:27,020
Now, you might be thinking, how are you going to generalize that?

176
00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:29,982
There's, like, the hand could be relative to the head, to the arm,

177
00:10:30,642 --> 00:10:34,345
any number of joints on the other character's skeleton, and vice versa.

178
00:10:34,365 --> 00:10:36,787
Are you going to put that many joints in the skeleton?

179
00:10:37,507 --> 00:10:40,409
One of our really clever engineers, Dominic Parker,

180
00:10:40,509 --> 00:10:42,891
figured out a way of encoding that information in the rig

181
00:10:42,951 --> 00:10:44,932
so that we could do it with a limited number of slots,

182
00:10:45,312 --> 00:10:47,414
and it would blend across animations.

183
00:10:47,474 --> 00:10:49,635
That's kind of the secret sauce of this solution.

184
00:10:50,135 --> 00:10:53,438
But if you have like a limited number of joints you want to make relative to each other,

185
00:10:53,518 --> 00:10:56,200
the bone approach is pretty much exactly what we're doing here.

186
00:10:56,941 --> 00:11:00,263
So we bake out the path of the hand relative to the head all throughout the animation,

187
00:11:01,124 --> 00:11:08,929
and the animators can author a curve that defines how tightly the hand is following that constraint.

188
00:11:09,110 --> 00:11:13,253
So it can become relative to the head, it can kind of ramp in as it starts approaching the head,

189
00:11:13,833 --> 00:11:17,796
be at 100% when he's holding the head, and then ramp back down to zero as he lets go.

190
00:11:18,837 --> 00:11:23,902
So when we play back this long-armed character on the same animation,

191
00:11:24,322 --> 00:11:28,126
we now have a target point for the hand relative to the other guy's head.

192
00:11:28,506 --> 00:11:32,610
We just snap it to there using IK, and away we go.

193
00:11:32,630 --> 00:11:36,274
So this is what that simple example looks like

194
00:11:36,874 --> 00:11:38,376
once you turn on the relative IK system.

195
00:11:39,397 --> 00:11:40,218
Pretty decent results.

196
00:11:42,675 --> 00:11:46,037
So, that works well for when the arm gets really long,

197
00:11:46,578 --> 00:11:47,959
and you need to figure out where to put it.

198
00:11:48,579 --> 00:11:51,201
What happens if the top fighter's head gets really, really big?

199
00:11:51,441 --> 00:11:53,042
That same approach doesn't work.

200
00:11:54,643 --> 00:11:57,085
So what we did, this is new for UFC 2.

201
00:11:57,646 --> 00:12:01,408
In the talk last year, I was saying that we wanted to move our IK system

202
00:12:01,609 --> 00:12:06,252
into the physics system, because we're having a lot of fighting between the IK and physics.

203
00:12:06,860 --> 00:12:09,682
One would be pulling in one direction, I could be pulling in the other, and you'd never really

204
00:12:09,742 --> 00:12:10,383
resolve anything.

205
00:12:10,923 --> 00:12:16,268
We accomplished that, and it gave us some new tools to use when trying to calculate

206
00:12:16,308 --> 00:12:16,968
these constraints.

207
00:12:17,489 --> 00:12:22,673
So what we do now is we cast a ray from the head to the hand.

208
00:12:23,214 --> 00:12:26,834
and figure out where that ray intersects with the collision volumes.

209
00:12:27,194 --> 00:12:30,895
And then we use those collision points on the surface of the mesh

210
00:12:31,235 --> 00:12:32,996
to define the relative constraints.

211
00:12:33,136 --> 00:12:34,716
So now, as the head gets bigger,

212
00:12:35,696 --> 00:12:38,357
the relative contact point moves out

213
00:12:38,437 --> 00:12:43,018
depending on the arbitrary size and shape of the collision geometry

214
00:12:43,418 --> 00:12:43,978
that's underneath.

215
00:12:47,019 --> 00:12:48,639
So, let's look at that in action.

216
00:12:48,819 --> 00:12:50,120
If I grow the top guy's head...

217
00:12:51,326 --> 00:12:53,066
and grow the bottom guy's arm,

218
00:12:54,527 --> 00:12:56,807
you'll see the results that you'd expect.

219
00:12:57,567 --> 00:12:59,008
The animation plays back.

220
00:13:01,888 --> 00:13:04,689
So that's a simple example, but in our game,

221
00:13:05,949 --> 00:13:07,329
we've got animations like this,

222
00:13:08,349 --> 00:13:11,870
where the characters are all tangled up like spaghetti.

223
00:13:12,390 --> 00:13:15,211
So someone has to go in and author all those constraints.

224
00:13:15,391 --> 00:13:18,491
Now, that was a huge time-consuming process in UFC 1.

225
00:13:19,792 --> 00:13:23,133
One of our engineers, John Tu, wrote an offline batch process

226
00:13:23,153 --> 00:13:24,953
to go through and analyze all the motion,

227
00:13:25,453 --> 00:13:28,534
figure out which joints were in close proximity to others

228
00:13:28,614 --> 00:13:31,055
and where they settled, and came up with a first pass

229
00:13:31,095 --> 00:13:32,696
of all the constraint authoring on these.

230
00:13:32,976 --> 00:13:34,356
And then sometimes they would work,

231
00:13:34,416 --> 00:13:35,156
sometimes they wouldn't.

232
00:13:35,236 --> 00:13:36,537
Animators would have to go through and...

233
00:13:38,118 --> 00:13:41,100
Tweak them in some cases just a little bit, in other cases a lot.

234
00:13:42,201 --> 00:13:45,084
But we were able to speed up the process by automating that stuff,

235
00:13:45,384 --> 00:13:50,128
and every single animation in the game has a set of these constraints built into it.

236
00:13:50,649 --> 00:13:54,252
That's kind of the base set of building blocks that I had to work with

237
00:13:55,073 --> 00:13:56,895
when putting together this procedural solution.

238
00:13:57,547 --> 00:14:02,092
Now, I've talked about using this for skill compensation,

239
00:14:02,132 --> 00:14:03,614
but it can also be used for other techniques.

240
00:14:04,475 --> 00:14:07,258
One that we use often in UFC 1 is animating

241
00:14:07,318 --> 00:14:09,720
against a static punching dummy.

242
00:14:10,061 --> 00:14:11,723
So you have a guy on top of another guy,

243
00:14:11,783 --> 00:14:14,325
and the bottom guy's animation is perfectly still.

244
00:14:15,006 --> 00:14:15,927
