So we had a spectrum here.

495
00:25:59,557 --> 00:26:01,878
I was aiming for fully procedural

496
00:26:01,918 --> 00:26:04,120
because you get all the memory savings from that.

497
00:26:04,860 --> 00:26:05,821
Obviously, a lot less work.

498
00:26:06,621 --> 00:26:09,002
But we were sitting in a place where we knew not everything

499
00:26:09,042 --> 00:26:09,783
was going to work that way.

500
00:26:09,863 --> 00:26:12,764
What we didn't know is how many would fall

501
00:26:12,824 --> 00:26:14,325
in which part of the spectrum.

502
00:26:15,145 --> 00:26:17,966
So we had the following concerns coming out of PrePro.

503
00:26:18,227 --> 00:26:19,747
Huge memory concerns, because if we

504
00:26:19,767 --> 00:26:21,628
have to do a tenfold increase in animations

505
00:26:21,708 --> 00:26:23,189
without increasing our memory budget,

506
00:26:23,549 --> 00:26:24,650
we just can't do this feature.

507
00:26:25,070 --> 00:26:26,310
The other one was the quality concerns.

508
00:26:26,371 --> 00:26:27,931
How many are going to be on the mocap side?

509
00:26:27,991 --> 00:26:29,872
How many are going to be on this fully procedural side?

510
00:26:30,472 --> 00:26:32,213
And are we going to be able to create enough content

511
00:26:32,874 --> 00:26:33,494
to support this?

512
00:26:35,689 --> 00:26:40,598
One of our brilliant engineers, Sam Rigamonte, put together an animation streaming solution for us.

513
00:26:40,698 --> 00:26:42,963
So, I'm not going to go into a ton of detail here, but...

514
00:26:43,861 --> 00:26:45,962
Because of the rigid nature of our state machine,

515
00:26:47,242 --> 00:26:51,664
if you're idling in state A, you have all those red lines

516
00:26:52,364 --> 00:26:53,305
already loaded in memory.

517
00:26:53,485 --> 00:26:54,905
If the guy presses on the stick, you

518
00:26:54,925 --> 00:26:56,766
can just play that animation because it's

519
00:26:56,926 --> 00:26:57,687
resident in memory.

520
00:26:58,207 --> 00:26:59,547
As soon as you play an animation that

521
00:26:59,587 --> 00:27:02,709
transitions you from A to B, we unload all the animations

522
00:27:02,749 --> 00:27:05,610
that come out of state A, start loading all the animations that

523
00:27:05,650 --> 00:27:06,330
come out of state B.

524
00:27:07,030 --> 00:27:13,152
And as long as you can load all those animations in the same amount of time that it takes you to play back the animation from A to B, you're golden.

525
00:27:13,812 --> 00:27:15,092
And he got the system working.

526
00:27:15,932 --> 00:27:18,413
So now we're sitting in a place where memory is not a concern.

527
00:27:18,993 --> 00:27:24,014
And we have a system that will scale up ridiculously big for future iterations of the game.

528
00:27:24,074 --> 00:27:27,095
So, super excited about that. Memory is no longer a concern.

529
00:27:28,295 --> 00:27:29,695
The big concern was the quality.

530
00:27:29,815 --> 00:27:35,656
We had no idea if we could get this done on time or to a quality level that was necessary to ship the game.

531
00:27:36,353 --> 00:27:37,593
So we kind of took a leap of faith here.

532
00:27:38,173 --> 00:27:39,174
There was nothing else we could do.

533
00:27:40,734 --> 00:27:44,555
We mitigated risk by focusing on workflow efficiencies

534
00:27:45,115 --> 00:27:48,036
and prioritizing the work just in case we ran out of time

535
00:27:48,076 --> 00:27:49,636
and coming up with some backup plans for some

536
00:27:49,656 --> 00:27:51,456
of the more fringe positions in the game.

537
00:27:52,957 --> 00:27:54,797
So that led us into production.

538
00:27:57,058 --> 00:27:57,618
Big unknowns.

539
00:27:58,198 --> 00:27:59,518
Not really sure if this is going to work,

540
00:27:59,899 --> 00:28:02,099
but a plan in place that kind of feels like maybe it would.

541
00:28:03,219 --> 00:28:04,540
And Jeremy will take you through production.

542
00:28:06,215 --> 00:28:06,456
Hello.

543
00:28:06,776 --> 00:28:07,136
Oh, sorry.

544
00:28:13,242 --> 00:28:15,584
Okay, so next we're gonna talk about

545
00:28:15,984 --> 00:28:18,126
the animation side of EA Sports UFC 2.

546
00:28:19,047 --> 00:28:21,349
And I think the best place to start is UFC 1.

547
00:28:21,569 --> 00:28:23,451
So, I wanna turn it back to UFC 1

548
00:28:23,931 --> 00:28:27,895
and talk about our approach to workflow there.

549
00:28:28,735 --> 00:28:31,656
I want to talk about the early design and workflow approach.

550
00:28:32,176 --> 00:28:34,797
I want to talk about the changes we faced,

551
00:28:36,098 --> 00:28:38,659
and the challenges we faced, sorry, and post-mortem.

552
00:28:40,199 --> 00:28:44,041
So UFC 1, the way we faced the feature

553
00:28:44,221 --> 00:28:45,822
was the way that probably anybody does.

554
00:28:45,982 --> 00:28:48,923
I'd meet with Liam Miller, our lead game designer,

555
00:28:49,103 --> 00:28:50,384
and we'd break down that feature

556
00:28:50,444 --> 00:28:51,544
and see kind of what he had in mind.

557
00:28:55,756 --> 00:29:01,818
Next, I would collect any visual reference that would help solidify this feature in my mind

558
00:29:01,858 --> 00:29:03,578
and make sure that was the same page as everybody else.

559
00:29:13,601 --> 00:29:14,121
Ah, there we go.

560
00:29:15,601 --> 00:29:20,403
And then, what we'd do often is either use a piece of paper or use a camera.

561
00:29:20,443 --> 00:29:22,603
We'd go in and we would break down.

562
00:29:23,749 --> 00:29:24,930
the individual parts of that feature.

563
00:29:25,571 --> 00:29:28,513
This is an example of a transition on the ground.

564
00:29:28,753 --> 00:29:31,014
All our transitions, for the most part, have five parts.

565
00:29:32,015 --> 00:29:36,378
Here you see Jeff and Liam are starting in the full guard position.

566
00:29:36,959 --> 00:29:40,421
If the player were to press right on the stick, they would get a start animation,

567
00:29:41,002 --> 00:29:42,483
then they would enter a ready animation,

568
00:29:42,903 --> 00:29:47,086
and depending on their inputs, they would either get a success, a deny, or a cancel animation.

569
00:29:50,752 --> 00:29:55,295
So now, knowing that each transition has five parts

570
00:29:55,355 --> 00:29:58,457
and how many transitions, I can then create a shot list

571
00:29:58,837 --> 00:30:00,519
for Motion Capture Studio.

572
00:30:01,840 --> 00:30:04,822
On the bottom right, you'll see a pose library there.

573
00:30:05,642 --> 00:30:08,504
That particular pose library has 87 pages

574
00:30:10,065 --> 00:30:12,207
with several poses on each page.

575
00:30:13,248 --> 00:30:14,489
That's not even all our poses.

576
00:30:15,189 --> 00:30:17,070
That's our Bible when we go in.

577
00:30:17,110 --> 00:30:18,511
That's our visual reference to show the actors.

578
00:30:23,247 --> 00:30:26,168
and then we go in to the studio and we capture the data.

579
00:30:27,608 --> 00:30:29,549
If you look on the right-hand screen,

580
00:30:29,749 --> 00:30:31,790
Liam Miller is weighing down the cage,

581
00:30:31,930 --> 00:30:33,470
and beside him is that closed library.

582
00:30:33,490 --> 00:30:34,871
That thing's essential.

583
00:30:34,891 --> 00:30:40,453
And then, using proprietary software,

584
00:30:40,653 --> 00:30:43,054
I'll go back to my desk, and I will painstakingly

585
00:30:43,114 --> 00:30:44,575
and tediously order that data.

586
00:30:45,275 --> 00:30:46,315
It's not a fun process.

587
00:30:48,608 --> 00:30:51,070
And then for UFC 1 we would clean it up in-house.

588
00:30:51,750 --> 00:30:53,991
This is Dmitri Kuprin, one of our senior animators,

589
00:30:54,071 --> 00:30:56,493
cleaning up a grapple transition.

590
00:31:00,955 --> 00:31:04,197
And then we'd review and revise to a shippable quality.

591
00:31:05,318 --> 00:31:07,219
This animation is still in the revision stage,

592
00:31:07,339 --> 00:31:10,181
but it's in good shape. It's getting there.

593
00:31:12,342 --> 00:31:13,963
So, why do we do it this way?

594
00:31:16,914 --> 00:31:19,916
We had the time and we had the headcount. We had a headcount of one

595
00:31:20,616 --> 00:31:22,298
and we figured that would be enough for this feature.

596
00:31:24,139 --> 00:31:28,762
And I was worried that the complexities of mixed martial arts and jujitsu

597
00:31:29,863 --> 00:31:32,365
would be lost in translation using STRL development.

598
00:31:33,085 --> 00:31:36,347
The sport is very technical. Our fans are very knowledgeable

599
00:31:37,028 --> 00:31:38,829
and they would know if we messed up.

600
00:31:39,670 --> 00:31:40,850
Grips have to be just so.

601
00:31:42,111 --> 00:31:43,372
posing just has to be just so.

602
00:31:43,392 --> 00:31:45,932
I was wrong in this assumption.

603
00:31:46,413 --> 00:31:48,133
For UFC 2, we did use external development,

604
00:31:48,753 --> 00:31:50,014
and it was to a huge success.

605
00:31:50,414 --> 00:31:53,315
If you guys want to hear more specifically how we did that,

606
00:31:53,775 --> 00:31:56,376
Sego Tanaka and I did a presentation at XDS

607
00:31:56,476 --> 00:31:58,617
last July in Vancouver.

608
00:31:58,917 --> 00:32:00,398
So if you want to find out more about that.

609
00:32:03,559 --> 00:32:06,800
So working that way, we ended up with 600 two-player

610
00:32:07,740 --> 00:32:09,181
grapple animations for UFC 1.

611
00:32:10,830 --> 00:32:17,372
The problems we faced working this way, our name convention discipline was lacking.

612
00:32:20,093 --> 00:32:25,554
Some animators named, for example, our half-guard position, half-guard, others named it half-G,

613
00:32:26,035 --> 00:32:30,336
some people named it start for the start animation, others attempt.

614
00:32:30,996 --> 00:32:32,796
Neither are wrong, but they are inconsistent.

615
00:32:34,280 --> 00:32:36,921
And that made our implementation less effective

616
00:32:36,941 --> 00:32:38,882
when searching out these particular assets.

617
00:32:40,582 --> 00:32:43,564
Problems like that, and other problems

618
00:32:43,584 --> 00:32:46,145
completely different, led to overtime,

619
00:32:46,725 --> 00:32:47,926
led to late implementation,

620
00:32:47,966 --> 00:32:49,546
which led to poor testing, poor tuning.

621
00:32:53,908 --> 00:32:54,969
Did I skip something there?

622
00:32:55,689 --> 00:32:55,849
Nope.

623
00:32:57,069 --> 00:32:58,750
So, postmortem coming out of that.

624
00:33:02,048 --> 00:33:04,670
We decided right away we definitely needed a tighter name convention.

625
00:33:08,072 --> 00:33:10,413
Because of the animation number was limited,

626
00:33:10,913 --> 00:33:15,176
this made the ground game feel linear, limited, it was turn-based,

627
00:33:16,256 --> 00:33:17,957
and visual feedback was lacking.

628
00:33:19,658 --> 00:33:22,660
We ended up with a 7 out of 10 on Metacritic, we really wanted that 8 out of 10.

629
00:33:25,082 --> 00:33:26,022
We needed a bigger game.

630
00:33:27,443 --> 00:33:28,584
We needed more animations.

631
00:33:29,619 --> 00:33:31,581
and I needed to embrace external development.

632
00:33:34,403 --> 00:33:36,805
So, moving into UFC 2's production cycle,

633
00:33:37,866 --> 00:33:40,749
I want to talk about the prototype of the ground game,

634
00:33:42,651 --> 00:33:43,651
preparing for production,

635
00:33:45,033 --> 00:33:46,013
and then production itself.

636
00:33:47,835 --> 00:33:48,796
So, the prototype.

637
00:33:49,977 --> 00:33:51,618
Early in pre-pro, Jeff came to me.

638
00:33:52,325 --> 00:33:54,166
And he said, hey, Jer, I got something to show you.

639
00:33:54,186 --> 00:33:56,648
And I came over to his desk, and he showed me

640
00:33:57,188 --> 00:33:59,169
his version of the ground game very early on.

641
00:33:59,730 --> 00:34:01,411
And it looked smooth, and it looked organic,

642
00:34:01,431 --> 00:34:03,072
it looked real, and it was really exciting.

643
00:34:03,092 --> 00:34:04,253
I said, how'd you get this?

644
00:34:04,733 --> 00:34:06,094
And he said, well, I have this nifty new

645
00:34:06,234 --> 00:34:07,175
grapple controller tool.

646
00:34:08,395 --> 00:34:10,097
And he said, I just want to show you

647
00:34:10,117 --> 00:34:11,598
which kind of data it's coming out of this tool.

648
00:34:11,878 --> 00:34:14,440
So he had me mock up a mixed idle,

649
00:34:14,540 --> 00:34:15,720
which I'll explain more about later.

650
00:34:16,401 --> 00:34:18,042
And he put through two existing

651
00:34:20,067 --> 00:34:22,788
UFC won assets and kind of mixed them together.

652
00:34:23,529 --> 00:34:26,591
And what we got was this kind of weird

653
00:34:27,451 --> 00:34:29,852
programmer art, linear animation.

654
00:34:30,733 --> 00:34:32,514
I looked at it, I'm like, well that's interesting.

655
00:34:32,554 --> 00:34:33,755
I looked at it again and I thought,

656
00:34:33,795 --> 00:34:36,296
well, our mocap isn't that great either.

657
00:34:36,916 --> 00:34:39,958
And this data comes with the begin pose

658
00:34:39,998 --> 00:34:42,259
and the end pose already imprinted and perfect.

659
00:34:42,720 --> 00:34:44,180
and all I have to do is clamp the in-between poses.

660
00:34:44,600 --> 00:34:47,041
And I'm like, that's actually kind of really cool.

661
00:34:47,521 --> 00:34:49,221
So I was like, let's see where this goes.

662
00:34:49,261 --> 00:34:50,001
I like this so far.

663
00:34:52,942 --> 00:34:54,522
So we kind of started to break it down.

664
00:34:54,562 --> 00:34:55,743
Like, what if we did it the old way?

665
00:34:56,043 --> 00:34:57,863
And we would have to do a lot of our assets the old way,

666
00:34:57,903 --> 00:34:59,143
but what if we do everything the old way?

667
00:35:01,244 --> 00:35:03,244
You know, I still have to do it with Liam or Jeff

668
00:35:03,384 --> 00:35:04,825
and figure out how this is all gonna work.

669
00:35:04,845 --> 00:35:08,085
I still have to gather my visual reference

670
00:35:08,206 --> 00:35:10,006
for the motion capture, make sure we're all on the same page.

671
00:35:11,930 --> 00:35:14,571
I still have to create these mix titles, which I'll talk about more later.

672
00:35:17,092 --> 00:35:17,953
Break down the design.

673
00:35:20,814 --> 00:35:22,855
Figure out that name convention, super important.

674
00:35:24,616 --> 00:35:27,217
Create the shot list, not fun, takes a long time.

675
00:35:28,737 --> 00:35:31,218
Go in, shoot the data, can be fun, not always fun.

676
00:35:33,139 --> 00:35:36,541
Order the data, which always sucks, no one likes doing it.

677
00:35:38,635 --> 00:35:40,136
And if we did it the old way, we'd clean up in-house,

678
00:35:40,416 --> 00:35:42,297
which we wouldn't this time, we'll use the actual development.

679
00:35:42,357 --> 00:35:43,657
Some of it in-house, some of it external.

680
00:35:44,938 --> 00:35:47,539
And then review and revise to a shipable quality.

681
00:35:48,879 --> 00:35:50,500
So we knew we couldn't do the whole game that way.

682
00:35:50,740 --> 00:35:52,461
So what if we used Jeff's tool?

683
00:35:54,321 --> 00:35:56,762
So for the procedural data, we'd make our mixed titles.

684
00:35:58,063 --> 00:36:00,083
We'd throw it through Jeff's nifty tool.

685
00:36:01,224 --> 00:36:02,224
We'd press export.

686
00:36:03,485 --> 00:36:06,346
Ideally, we'd ship it off to Technicolor in India.

687
00:36:07,767 --> 00:36:08,968
you know, we're good.

688
00:36:10,169 --> 00:36:12,591
So we decided we're going to try that.

689
00:36:12,771 --> 00:36:13,912
Let's prepare for production.

690
00:36:14,072 --> 00:36:15,433
Let's see how we're going to do this all.

691
00:36:17,695 --> 00:36:19,597
So I'm going to first talk about the mixed idle,

692
00:36:19,677 --> 00:36:21,178
so we all know what that means.

693
00:36:22,599 --> 00:36:25,542
On the left, you'll see our regular full guard position.

694
00:36:26,182 --> 00:36:30,566
If the top man presses left on the stick, he gets this idle.

695
00:36:31,707 --> 00:36:34,249
Now if we go back to our default guard idle,

696
00:36:34,309 --> 00:36:36,591
if the bottom man presses left on his stick,

697
00:36:37,998 --> 00:36:42,121
we get sorry at the bottom model there in the middle and then if they both press left on the stick

698
00:36:43,963 --> 00:36:48,127
You'll see here in the full guard position the top man's right elbow

699
00:36:49,205 --> 00:36:53,149
You'll see here in his pose, he's digging into the bottom man's left leg.

700
00:36:53,810 --> 00:37:01,698
You'll see again in the far left picture, the bottom man's left wrist is now going for the arm drag.

701
00:37:02,619 --> 00:37:04,961
It's around the top man's left tricep.

702
00:37:05,501 --> 00:37:07,443
And in our mixed title, when they both press left of the stick,

703
00:37:08,204 --> 00:37:12,588
the top man's right elbow is digging into the bottom man's leg, while at the same time,

704
00:37:13,349 --> 00:37:16,713
the bottom man's left wrist hand is gripping the, whoops,

705
00:37:17,333 --> 00:37:19,035
gripping the top man's tricep.

706
00:37:19,335 --> 00:37:21,838
Perfect, that's what we need.

707
00:37:21,858 --> 00:37:24,420
So, we now had to figure out what kind of data

708
00:37:24,460 --> 00:37:25,501
was gonna come out of this tool,

709
00:37:25,641 --> 00:37:27,243
so we knew how to best prepare for that.

710
00:37:28,592 --> 00:37:31,033
We did like a vertical slice of the guard position.

711
00:37:31,053 --> 00:37:33,194
We kind of did some quick math out of that.

712
00:37:33,875 --> 00:37:36,216
So we figured, based on the guard position,

713
00:37:36,256 --> 00:37:38,917
that 80% of our data would be easy to process.

714
00:37:39,817 --> 00:37:42,519
It would take about 1.5 man hours

715
00:37:42,619 --> 00:37:44,479
to clean up each little transition.

716
00:37:44,519 --> 00:37:48,541
10% of the data would be difficult to process.

717
00:37:49,755 --> 00:37:53,537
Going back to the easy to process, that would also be great to send to our show of developments, easy for them.

718
00:37:54,457 --> 00:38:01,340
Difficult to process is 10%, that would be 3 man hours, and those would be awkward to explain to our show of developments.

719
00:38:01,400 --> 00:38:05,182
We thought, let's just keep that in-house, it's a small number, it would be perfect to keep in-house.

720
00:38:06,203 --> 00:38:13,426
And then 10% would be, cannot process, we'll have to go through that whole motion capture process.

721
00:38:13,706 --> 00:38:17,468
And then once that's done, it would be about 4 hours for a person in the studio to clean it up.

722
00:38:20,970 --> 00:38:23,313
So just an example of easy to process data.

723
00:38:24,514 --> 00:38:28,437
This was the kind of data we were getting for the most part from the tool.

724
00:38:29,218 --> 00:38:34,803
The bottom man's right arm is going through the top man's left arm

725
00:38:35,463 --> 00:38:38,827
and the bottom man's legs are crossing through each other.

726
00:38:39,407 --> 00:38:40,308
It's very linear.

727
00:38:41,649 --> 00:38:43,931
It's not bad, it's definitely something we can work with,

728
00:38:44,011 --> 00:38:45,192
but it's not perfect as you can see.

729
00:38:45,272 --> 00:38:47,735
So that's about 1.5 hours for a person to clean up.

730
00:38:50,198 --> 00:38:57,424
Difficult to process data, this is a bit trickier. It looks kind of simple at first, but the top man's right arm is going through the bottom man's left arm.

731
00:38:58,004 --> 00:39:03,489
So, we're going to have to explain to a person, you've got to bring that wrist all the way to his hip to pull it through.

732
00:39:03,509 --> 00:39:08,653
We'll probably have to separate the two, the top man will have to push off a bit separating their bodies, and then we'll have to pin the legs.

733
00:39:09,414 --> 00:39:11,636
Rather than try to explain that, we'll keep it in-house, keep it simple.

734
00:39:14,205 --> 00:39:23,010
